courses.name: Japan in the World, mid-16th to mid-20th century

cmCourseInfo.description: This course examines Japan within the context of world history from the mid-16th to the mid-20th century. Rather than seek comprehensive coverage of Japan's national history along a linear timeline, we will use Japan as a lens through which to consider key moments in the history of the modern world.
cmCourseInfo.title: Japan in the World, Mid-16th to Mid-20th century
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: One course from: HIS102Y1, HIS103Y1, HIS107Y1, HIS241H1, HIS242H1, HIS244H1, HIS250H1, HIS250Y1, HIS271Y1, HIS280Y1, HIS281Y1, HIS282Y1, HIS283Y1, HIS291H1, HIS291Y1, HIS292H1, HIS292Y1, HIS297Y1, or 1.0 credit from CAS200H1, CAS201H1, CAS202H1, CAS310H1, CAS320H1.

cmCourseInfo.description: This course focuses on the use of neuroimaging techniques in understanding how trauma, disorders, and disease impact neural structure and function. Lectures will focus on introduction to techniques and clinical/research applications. Lab work will focus on the development of practical skills including image processing, analyses, and experimental design.
cmCourseInfo.title: Clinical Neuroimaging
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Completion of 9.0 credits including PSL300H1, BIO230H1, and one of HMB200H1/ PSY290H1/ ANA300Y1

notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This course will be part of HMB pre-enrolment. Eligible program students will receive a ballot via email in early in early June to rank eligible 400-level courses in order of preference, with decisions confirmed pre-enrolment complete before the start of course enrolment. Please see the HMB Course Match FAQ for details. Students who are not pre-enrolled in the course but meet the enrolment controls will be able to enroll or waitlist for the course once course enrolment starts.
